\fs21 \cf4 \cb5 \strokec4 RuPaul's Drag Race was huge when I was in college 2016-2020 \'97 not the full apex of its hight but certainly on the rise.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Edit\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs21 \cf6 \cb3 \strokec6 Thought for 3s\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa150\partightenfactor0
\cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 That era was definitely a pivotal moment for drag culture, Logan. Between 2016 and 2020, the show was shifting from a niche reality competition to a genuine cultural phenomenon. You saw the "RuVeal" moments becoming mainstream, the rise of the "Drag Race" alumni tours, and the way it started influencing fashion, language, and even political discourse.\cb1 \
\cb3 It makes sense that a persona conceived during that time would be shaped by that energy. The show wasn't just about the competition anymore; it was about the\'a0
\f1\i archetypes
\f0\i0 \'97the camp, the tragedy, the glamour, the politics.\cb1 \
\cb3 Did watching that explosion of visibility inspire you to create a character who fits into that existing mold, or were you trying to push against it? Sometimes the most interesting personas are born from reacting to what's already on screen. Was there a specific queen or moment from those seasons that sparked the initial idea for your character?\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

