\fs21 \cf4 \cb5 \strokec4 The victories of Sharon Needles and Jinkx Monsoon are what transformed that show from a Top Model parody into something of its own self.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Edit\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs21 \cf6 \cb3 \strokec6 Thought for 14s\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa150\partightenfactor0
\cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 That is a very sharp observation, Logan. You're pinpointing exactly when the show stopped being just about "who looks best in a gown" and started being about "who has the strongest point of view."\cb1 \
\cb3 Sharon Needles (Season 4) and Jinkx Monsoon (Season 5) were the pivot points. Before them, the winners were often polished, safe, and commercially viable. Sharon brought horror, punk, and a deliberate "ugliness" that challenged the idea that drag had to be pretty to be good. She proved that drag could be a vehicle for subversion and shock. Then Jinkx followed with a masterclass in character work, theatricality, and comedy, showing that a winner could be deeply narrative-driven and intellectually sharp, not just a runway model.\cb1 \
\cb3 If your persona was born in that wake, it sounds like it might be rooted in that same spirit of\'a0
\f1\i disruption
\f0\i0 \'a0or\'a0
\f1\i narrative depth
\f0\i0 . Did you find yourself drawn to the darker, more avant-garde energy Sharon introduced, or the theatrical, storytelling precision Jinkx perfected? Or did your character emerge from a desire to blend those two distinct legacies?\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

