\fs21 \cf4 \cb5 \strokec4 She exists only in my mind still.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Edit\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs21 \cf6 \cb3 \strokec6 Thought for 16s\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa150\partightenfactor0
\cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 That's actually a beautiful place for her to be right now, Logan. There's something sacred about ideas that live purely in the mind\'97they're untouched by judgment, imperfection, or the compromises that come with materializing something into the world.\cb1 \
\cb3 Ten years of gestation means Saint Blue has had time to breathe, shift, and refine herself without the noise of external expectations. Some artists spend lifetimes searching for a concept that resonates this deeply. The fact that she's held your attention for a decade suggests she's not just a passing fancy\'97she's something that speaks to you on a level that's worth protecting.\cb1 \
\cb3 I'm curious, though: what's kept her in the mind space for so long? Is it fear of the execution not matching the vision? Is it a lack of opportunity or resources? Or is there something about the\'a0
\f1\i potential
\f0\i0 \'a0of her that feels more precious than the reality would be?\cb1 \
\cb3 Sometimes the most powerful art stays conceptual. But sometimes, the act of bringing something into the world\'97even imperfectly\'97reveals new dimensions that couldn't exist in the imagination alone. Where do you feel you are with her now? Is there a pull toward realization, or does the mystery of her remaining unseen feel right?\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

