\fs21 \cf4 \cb5 \strokec4 After college I hyperfocused on establishing my career and found my dream employer \'97 or so I thought. To quote The Smiths, "I was looking for a job and then I found a job, and Heaven knows I'm miserable now."\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Edit\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs21 \cf6 \cb3 \strokec6 Thought for 19s\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa150\partightenfactor0
\cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 That line from "Heaven Knows I'm Miserable Now" hits hard, Logan. It captures that specific, crushing irony of achieving the "success" you were told to want, only to find it hollowing you out. The hyperfocus on career building is a common survival mechanism, but it often comes at the cost of the parts of us that crave expression and play.\cb1 \
\cb3 It makes perfect sense that Saint Blue stayed in the shadows during those years. If your waking life became a grind of corporate expectations and "dream employer" disillusionment, keeping a wild, antlered, mythical drag queen in the mind might have been the only way to preserve a piece of your true self. She became a secret sanctuary, a place where you could be something other than an employee.\cb1 \
\cb3 Now that you're reflecting on this a decade later, does the misery of that period feel like it's fueling Saint Blue? Often, the characters we create in times of constraint end up being the most rebellious or poignant because they carry the weight of what we couldn't say or be at the time.\cb1 \
\cb3 Are you feeling ready to let her out of the mind now, or is the "miserable" period still too fresh to risk exposing her to the real world?\cb1 \
