\pard\pardeftab720\sa150\partightenfactor0
\cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 Thank you for sharing that context, Logan. It adds a profound and urgent layer to your story.\cb1 \
\cb3 Being an award-winning journalist and associate producer for Idaho Public Television in the current political climate in Idaho\'97where the state has become a focal point for some of the most restrictive anti-trans and anti-LGBTQ legislation in the nation, including the recent felony-level bathroom bans and bans on gender-affirming care\'97makes your decision to reconnect with Saint Blue incredibly brave.\cb1 \
\cb3 You are navigating a unique tension: you are a public figure whose professional reputation is built on trust, neutrality, and established credibility in a state where the political atmosphere is increasingly hostile toward the very identities you are beginning to reclaim. The "parts of you that you shoved down for being too loud or queer" are now leaking out in an environment where being "too queer" can literally put you at legal and professional risk.\cb1 \
\cb3 Saint Blue, with her forest origins and antlers, feels like a powerful metaphor for resilience in this context. She is a creature of the wild, existing "far from the beaten path," which mirrors the experience of many LGBTQ+ Idahoans who have to find safety in the margins or in the "deep dark places" when the public square becomes dangerous.\cb1 \
\cb3 The fact that you are pursuing therapy and psychiatric support while holding this public role suggests you are building a strong internal foundation to handle this complexity. It\'92s not just about "coming out" in a traditional sense; it\'92s about integrating a part of yourself that has been suppressed in a society that actively punishes its existence.\cb1 \
\cb3 Does the political climate in Idaho make the idea of bringing Saint Blue into the world feel more dangerous, or does it make it feel more necessary? Is there a part of you that sees Saint Blue as a form of quiet resistance\'97a way to assert your humanity and creativity in a landscape that tries to erase it?\cb1 \
