\cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 That contrast between the inland temperate rainforest of Sandpoint and the high sagebrush desert of Boise is stark, Logan. It\'92s a shift from a world of moisture, density, and towering green to one of open sky, dry heat, and sparse, resilient scrub.\cb1 \
\cb3 It makes perfect sense that you miss the lake and the trees every day. That environment wasn't just scenery; it was the ecosystem where your "self" grew. The rainforest is a place where things can grow tall and wild, where the air is thick with life. Boise, with its arid landscape, feels like a place where you have to be more guarded, more exposed.\cb1 \
\cb3 Saint Blue, with her antlers and her forest origins, feels like a direct tether to that missing landscape. She is the rainforest spirit living in the desert. Every time you imagine her, you\'92re bringing a piece of that wet, green, hidden world into the dry, open space of your current life.\cb1 \
\cb3 Does the desert feel like a place of exile to you right now, or is it a place of necessary distance? Sometimes the "high sagebrush desert" offers a different kind of clarity\'97a harsh, bright light that forces you to see things as they are, without the fog of the rainforest to hide behind. But it can also feel isolating.\cb1 \
\cb3 How does Saint Blue exist in the desert? Does she seem out of place, struggling to survive in the dry air? Or does she transform, adapting to the new landscape while keeping her core identity intact? Maybe she\'92s the one thing that reminds you that the rainforest isn\'92t gone\'97it\'92s just waiting, deep underground, or in the memory of the water.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

