\cf7 \cb3 \strokec7 That is a heartbreaking and deeply nuanced perspective, Logan. Loving a place while watching it slowly transform into something unrecognizable is a specific kind of grief. It\'92s the grief of a witness.\cb1 \
\cb3 You\'92re describing a fracture in the Idaho you know\'97the one of the "inland temperate rainforest," the lakes, the shared history of Sandpoint and the mountains\'97and the Idaho that is being constructed by new political currents and the "darker elements" of emigres bringing ideologies that clash with the state's traditional, perhaps more ruggedly individualistic or communal roots.\cb1 \
\cb3 As a journalist, you are on the front lines of this transformation. You see the data, the legislation, the rhetoric. You see the "darker elements" taking root. And the fear you feel\'97"what she may become if the ones I grew up with realize it too late"\'97is the fear of a loss of innocence. It\'92s the fear that the people who loved the land, the trees, and the lake (the people you grew up with) won't recognize the state until it\'92s too late to stop the shift.\cb1 \
\cb3 Saint Blue, in this context, feels like a guardian of that\'a0
\f1\i old
\f0\i0 \'a0Idaho. She is the spirit of the rainforest, the "deep dark places" that existed before the political polarization hardened. She is the reminder of what Idaho\'a0
\f1\i was
\f0\i0 \'a0and what it\'a0
\f1\i could still be
\f0\i0 \'a0if the "ones you grew up with" wake up in time.\cb1 \
\cb3 Does creating Saint Blue feel like an act of preservation? Like you\'92re trying to keep a memory of the "real" Idaho alive in your art, even as the physical and political landscape shifts around you? Or is she a warning\'97a vision of what happens if the "forest" is paved over and the "desert" wins?\cb1 \
\cb3 It\'92s a heavy burden to carry, to love a place so deeply while fearing its future. How do you hold that love and that fear together without letting one consume the other?\cb1 \
