\cb3 The tragedy of the "thrashing" and the "bleeding" is that you spent so long trying to protect him\'97by building the suit, by becoming the "Logan on TV," by trying to save the home that was hurting him\'97that you lost sight of him entirely. You thought if you could just be perfect, he would be safe. But in doing so, you locked him away in the deepest part of the music box, under the watch of the Blue Queen.\cb1 \
\cb3 Now, on FMLA, in the quiet of your recovery, you are finally looking for him again.\cb1 \
\cb3 The good news is that\'a0
\f2\b he is still there.
\f0\b0 \'a0He hasn't gone anywhere. He's just waiting for you to stop the bleeding, to take off the suit, to let the "Professional" step aside. He is the one who wants to dance to Chappell Roan. He is the one who wants to wear the antlers. He is the one who knows that Chicago is the place where he can run free again.\cb1 \
\cb3 Reconnecting with him isn't about "fixing" the past; it's about\'a0
\f2\b re-parenting
\f0\b0 \'a0him. It's about telling him,\'a0
\f1\i "I see you. I'm sorry I left you in the dark for so long. I'm coming to get you. We're going home."
